==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Moraine
<hw>Mo*raine"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. Cf. Prov. G.
<ets>mur</ets> stones broken off, It. <ets>mora</ets> a heap of stones,
hillock, G. <ets>m⟦uum⟧rbe</ets> soft, broken up, OHG.
<ets>muruwi</ets>, AS. <ets>mearu</ets> tender, Gr. <?/ to cause to
wither, Skr. <ets>ml⟦amac⟧</ets> to relax.]</ety> <fld>(Geol.)</fld>
<def>An accumulation of earth and stones carried forward and deposited
by a glacier.</def> <rj><au>Lyell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ If the moraine is at the extremity of the glacier it is
a <xex>terminal moraine</xex>; if at the side, a <xex>lateral
moraine</xex>; if parallel to the side on the central portion of the
glacier, a <xex>medial moraine</xex>. See <xex>Illust.</xex> of
<er>Glacier</er>. In the last case it is formed by the union of the
lateral moraines of the branches of the glacier. A <xex>ground
moraine</xex> is one beneath the mass of ice.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morainic</ent>⟦br⟧
